# Orca Community Edition — Contributor Workflow Guide

When a user says they want to contribute, submit a fix, open a PR, or improve something, guide them through this workflow step by step.

## Step 1: Determine the Contribution Type

Ask what they want to contribute:

| Type | Branch prefix | Example |
|------|--------------|---------|
| Bug fix | `fix/` | `fix/port-conflict-on-startup` |
| Feature | `feature/` | `feature/api-response-time-chart` |
| Documentation | `docs/` | `docs/windows-setup-instructions` |
| DX improvement | `dx/` | `dx/better-java-version-error` |
| Refactor | `refactor/` | `refactor/health-check-consolidation` |
| Test | `test/` | `test/deploy-endpoint-integration` |

## Step 2: Verify They're on a Fork

Check if the remote points to their fork (not the upstream repo):

```bash
git remote -v
```

- If `origin` points to `sivaji-orca/orca-community`, they need to fork first:
  1. Go to https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community and click "Fork"
  2. Then update their remote:
     ```bash
     git remote set-url origin https://github.com/<their-username>/orca-community.git
     git remote add upstream https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community.git
     ```

- If `origin` points to their fork, they're good. Verify `upstream` is set:
  ```bash
  git remote add upstream https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community.git 2>/dev/null || true
  ```

## Step 3: Create a Branch

Sync with upstream first, then create a branch:

```bash
git fetch upstream
git checkout main
git rebase upstream/main
git checkout -b <prefix>/<descriptive-name>
```

Use the branch prefix from Step 1.

## Step 4: Guide the Changes

Based on the contribution type, point them to the right files:

- **Backend code**: `backend/src/` — Express.js routes and services
- **Frontend code**: `frontend/src/` — React components and pages
- **MuleSoft projects**: `projects/` — Mule XML flows and RAML specs
- **Documentation**: `docs/` and root `.md` files
- **Scripts**: `scripts/` — bash scripts with `set -euo pipefail`
- **Cursor rules**: `.cursor/rules/` — `.mdc` files for AI guidance
- **Tests**: `backend/src/__tests__/` (Bun) and `frontend/src/__tests__/` (Vitest)

Remind them of code guidelines:
- Backend: `async/await`, consistent JSON responses `{ success, data/error }`
- Frontend: functional components, hooks, shadcn/ui components
- Scripts: `#!/usr/bin/env bash`, `set -euo pipefail`, colored output helpers

## Step 5: Run Tests

Before committing, ensure all checks pass:

```bash
# Backend tests
cd backend && bun test

# Frontend tests
cd frontend && bun run test

# Frontend lint
cd frontend && bun run lint
```

If tests fail, help them debug. If they've added a new endpoint or component, remind them to add tests.

## Step 6: Commit with Conventional Commits

Guide them to commit with the right format:

```
<type>(<scope>): <short description>
```

Types: `feat`, `fix`, `docs`, `style`, `refactor`, `test`, `chore`, `dx`
Scopes: `backend`, `frontend`, `scripts`, `deploy`, `postman`, `git`, `docs`, `ci`

Example:
```bash
git add -A
git commit -m "fix(backend): resolve port 3003 conflict when process already running"
```

## Step 7: Push and Create PR

```bash
git push origin <branch-name>
```

Then guide them to create a PR on GitHub:
1. Go to their fork on GitHub — there should be a banner to create a PR
2. Target: `sivaji-orca/orca-community` `main` branch
3. Fill out the PR template (type of change, changes, how to test, checklist)
4. Link any related issues with `Closes #<number>`

Or use the GitHub CLI:
```bash
gh pr create --repo sivaji-orca/orca-community --title "<type>(<scope>): description" --body "## Summary\n\n..."
```

## Step 8: After Submitting

Let them know:
- CI will run automatically (backend tests, frontend lint/build/tests)
- A maintainer will review within 48 hours
- They may get feedback — push new commits to the same branch to update the PR
- Don't force-push during review

## Opening an Issue Instead

If the contributor wants to report a roadblock or suggest an improvement without coding:

1. Go to https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community/issues/new/choose
2. Pick the right template:
   - **Bug Report** — something is broken
   - **Feature Request** — an idea for a new feature
   - **Documentation & DX Improvement** — confusing steps, missing docs, unclear errors
3. Fill out the template thoroughly
4. Or use GitHub Discussions for open-ended feedback: https://github.com/sivaji-orca/orca-community/discussions
